Project LUX

- NIR S

Wearable Time - Resolved Optical Brain Monitoring for Early Cognitive &

Neurological Risk Detection

---

LUX - NIR S Monitor is a Health Technology start - up founded to identify cognitive deterioration

and provide ongoing tracking of brain wellness via a wearable TR - fNIRS technology in

conjunction with machine - learning analysis. Our objective for this business plan is to assist

people in identifying the signs of cognitive decline, neurological stress, and cerebrovascular

dysfunction, long before symptoms manifest and become permanent disabilities.

While consumer EEG devices lack physiological specificity and spatial robustness, current brain

imaging tools like fMRI and PET are costly, immobile, and episodic. Lecture 6 emphasizes that

time - domain optical imaging is a significant advancement: TR - fNIRS can distinguish deep

cortical signals from superficial scalp contamination, a significant drawback of conventional

fNIRS, by measuring photon time - of - flight rather than intensity. Thanks to these developments,

reliable wearable brain monitoring is now pos sible outside of lab settings .

Before branching out into preventive consumer health, LUX - NIR S Monitor will first focus

on clinical and research markets, such as neurology clinics, rehabilitation facilities, and

long - term brain - health studies. LUX - NIRS Monitor product is a portable wearable headset

that continuously monitors blood flow proxies and cerebral oxygenation dynamics

throughout daily life. Cognitive fatigue, neurovascular coupling efficiency, and irregular

hemodynamic patterns linked to early dementia, concus sion, or stroke risk are just a few of

the validated brain - health metrics that the system converts optical signals into clinically

interpretable results; that can be monitored over time and contrasted with specific baseline

measurements. Compared to episodic imaging techniques. This longitudinal approach

supports earlier intervention, individualized monitoring, and more ecologically valid

assessments by allowin g researchers and clinicians to identify subtle changes in brain

function over time.

The business will continue to use a scalable hardware - plus - software business model while

operating under an FDA Class II medical device pathway with robust clinical validation. LUX -

NIR S Monitor intends to establish as a fundamental platform for ongoing brain monitoring over

the course of three years by completing clinical validation, regulatory clearance, and use across

partner clinics. In terms of practicality, LUX - NIRS Monitor builds upon technologies that have

already been demonstrated in research - grade systems, like the flexible fibre optics, single - photon

detection, time - domain optical imaging, and machine - learning - based signal proce ssing.

Although further development and validation are required, the essential elements are sufficiently

developed to support short - term translational efforts.

All things considered, this proposal captures the main idea of Lecture 6 , responsible application,

realistic deployment strategies, and careful integration are just as important to the future of

optical neuroimaging as technological innovation.

---

Scientific Foundation

The use of average light intensity as a measure for traditional fNIRS allows the measurement to

be subject to noise and interference caused by blood flow and scalp hair. However, TR - fNIRS

utilises picosecond laser pulses and single - photon detection technol ogy to obtain measurements

of photon arrival time and allows for the measurement of photon depth with absolute

physiological measurements.

Among the main benefits discussed in lecture 6 are:

‚Ä¢ Cortical and superficial signal separation

‚Ä¢ enhanced signal - to - noise in practical settings

‚Ä¢ Strong synergy with machine - learning - based signal processing

‚Ä¢ Compatibility with wearable, high - density arrays

LUX - NIR S business will use these benefits to build a clinically reliable yet portable brain

monitoring platform.

H ardware

1. VCSEL light sources used in fNIRS optodes in the time domain

2. Single photon sensitivity achieved with SiPM photodetectors

3. Flexible architecture for fNIRS created with fiber optics for comfort and tolerating long

hair

4. Streaming data wirelessly to mobile apps or clinical dashboard

Software

1. Removing artifacts from the real - time signal using adaptive machine learning due to

motion and ambient light

2. Automatic reconstruction of the depth - resolved signal

3. Developing metrics of brain health based on the dynamics of neurovascular function

4. Ability for long - term tracking of individual baselines through comparison

The LUX - NIRS Monitor diverges from other consumer neurofeedback devices because it does

not assert that it can ‚Äúread your mind.‚Äù The LUX - NIRS Monitor concentrates on established

physiological indicators and fits within the context of this lecture regarding realistic and

interpretable applications of neurotechnology, as opposed to speculation regarding future use

cases of BCI technology.

Technology Readiness Level (TRL) of the fNIRS System:

- The fNIRS technology is at TRL 6 - 7 with validated research systems such as Kernel

Flow

- T he wearable integration and machine learning (ML) pipeline are currently at TRL 5 - 6

---

- T he readiness for clinical use is at TRL 4 - 5 with the need for clinical trials to be

conducted.

This level of development places fNIRS as a near - term use commercial offering rather than a

long - range research program.

Why Right Now?

Several convergent patterns are explained in Lecture 6 that inspired the timeline of this business

plan to start now:

‚Ä¢ Photonics miniaturization (VCSELs, SiPMs)

‚Ä¢ The need for continuous, real - world brain measurements, similar to heart - rate monitors;

machine learning that can decipher meaning from noisy optical data

‚Ä¢ Growing awareness of concussions in sports and the workplace

‚Ä¢ Aging populations increase the burden of dementia

‚Ä¢ Preventive monitoring is becoming more common in healthcare systems.

The landscape of non - invasive brain monitoring today consists of consumer, research grade time

resolved systems, and continuous wave platforms for monitoring brain activity with fNIRS or

functional Near Infrared Spectroscopy (fNIRS). The former uses consum er devices like Muse

which allow for greater access to the general public, but cause a lack of sufficient depth

sensitivity making clinical interpretation nearly impossible. Research grade time - resolved

---

systems like Kernel Flow provide researchers with the ability to discriminate between different

depths of the brain, but still cost too much and are considered to be focused on research only.

Portable fNIRS systems made by companies like NIRx and Artinis a re available to researchers

for use in the field but are frequently compromised by superficial signal contamination, therefore

reducing their accuracy. The goal of Project LUX - NIRS is to integrate time - resolved imaging

into a wearable format for long - term real - world brain monitoring with sufficient depth analysis

and sensitivity

Project LUX - NIRS differentiates itself by combining:

‚Ä¢ Time - domain depth accuracy

‚Ä¢ Clinical validation

‚Ä¢ Wearable deployment at mid - range cost

The first three years' projected funding is relatively large but is based on a strategic model with a

focus on long - term affordability for users globally as opposed to the short - term

commercialization of products. Investing in R&D early will allow manufact urers to optimize the

cost of optical hardware, signal processing, and the design of the wearables, thus reducing unit

cost during mass manufacturing. Providing funding to validate the performance of the devices in

clinical trials will create solid perform ance standards that reduce the necessity of expensive

redesigns and allow for easier passage through the regulatory process. Manufacturers are

focusing on the production of photonic components, including VCSELs and silicon

photomultipliers, that can be mad e using economies of scale, as such components will

experience a decrease in cost over time as their production increases. As discussed in Lecture 6,

---

this strategy will help to move products from the lab stage to brain - monitoring technology that

will be readily available in a wide range of clinical and global settings.
